  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theory—it's a lived reality for many who've walked the path of learning and discovery. Growing up in a household where my parents both had vocational training, I saw firsthand how early assumptions about what kinds of people could excel in technical fields often shaped opportunities. When I was in high school, I remember being told by a teacher that 'girls aren't built for engineering'—a comment that stuck with me long after the class ended. That kind of bias isn't just harmful; it's a silent barrier that can make someone question their own abilities, especially when they're already trying to navigate a world that doesn't always see them as capable. As a transgender person who's worked in the field of photography and video games, I know that stereotypes can be even more complex when they intersect with gender identity. The idea that STEM is 'for boys' or 'for the logical minds' is a myth that needs to be dismantled. Addressing stereotype threat requires more than just awareness—it demands active steps like mentorship programs that pair students with role models who look like them, inclusive classrooms where everyone feels safe to ask questions, and a cultural shift that celebrates diverse talents without labeling them. In my community, I've seen how small changes, like having a female engineer lead a school project, can spark a ripple effect of confidence. We must address this issue because when people feel unseen, they don't just fall behind—they lose the spark that makes them want to innovate. It's not just about fixing a problem; it's about nurturing the next generation of thinkers who deserve to thrive.",
